Explain Full lifecycle of a request in Lambda plus API Gateway?

Best example — Food ordering app:

User places order on Swiggy/Zomato
        │
        ▼
POST https://api.swiggy.com/orders
Body: {
  "restaurant": "KFC",
  "item": "Burger",
  "quantity": 2
}

Tell them this flow:

Step 1 - User clicks "Place Order" button
         → HTTP POST request sent to API Gateway

Step 2 - API Gateway checks:
         → Is user logged in? (Auth)
         → Valid request format?
         → Not spamming? (Rate limit)

Step 3 - API Gateway triggers Lambda
         → Converts request to event object
         → Passes to lambda_handler

Step 4 - Lambda runs:
         → Checks restaurant is open
         → Calculates price
         → Saves order to DB
         → Sends notification to restaurant

Step 5 - Lambda returns response:
         → Order ID
         → Estimated delivery time

Step 6 - API Gateway sends back to user:
         → "Order placed successfully!"
         → "Delivery in 30 minutes"

Then mention cold start smartly:

Interviewer: "Any challenges with Lambda?"

You say:
"Yes, cold start is one challenge.
First request takes 2-3 seconds extra
because Lambda needs to initialize.

For example in Swiggy during off-peak hours
Lambda container gets destroyed after 15 mins idle.
Next order request hits cold start.

We fix this using:
├── Provisioned Concurrency → keeps Lambda warm
└── Smaller package size    → faster cold start"
